{"parse":{"title":"History of Jewish conversion to Christianity","pageid":55342140,"revid":830477649,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>There is a long history of Jewish <a href=\"/wiki/Conversion_to_Christianity\" title=\"Conversion to Christianity\">conversion to Christianity</a>, both voluntarily and <a href=\"/wiki/Forced_conversion\" title=\"Forced conversion\">forced conversion</a>. What follows is a partial history of some of the well known mass conversions.\n</p>\n<div id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\"><input type=\"checkbox\" role=\"button\" id=\"toctogglecheckbox\" class=\"toctogglecheckbox\" style=\"display:none\" /><div class=\"toctitle\" lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><h2>Contents</h2><span class=\"toctogglespan\"><label class=\"toctogglelabel\" for=\"toctogglecheckbox\"></label></span></div>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-1\"><a href=\"#Forced_conversions\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Forced conversions</span></a>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-2 tocsection-2\"><a href=\"#Middle_Ages\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1.1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Middle Ages</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-2 tocsection-3\"><a href=\"#Early_modern_Iberian_peninsula\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1.2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Early modern Iberian peninsula</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-2 tocsection-4\"><a href=\"#Eastern_Europe\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1.3</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Eastern Europe</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-2 tocsection-5\"><a href=\"#Post-Enlightenment\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1.4</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Post-Enlightenment</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-6\"><a href=\"#References\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">References</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Forced_conversions\">Forced conversions</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=History_of_Jewish_conversion_to_Christianity&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Forced conversions\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<h3><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Middle_Ages\">Middle Ages</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=History_of_Jewish_conversion_to_Christianity&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Middle Ages\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h3>\n<p>Forced conversions of Jews were carried out with support of rulers during Late Antiquity and the early Middle Ages in Gaul, the Iberian peninsula and in the Byzantine empire.<sup id=\"cite_ref-:0_1-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-:0-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>Royal persecutions of Jews from the late eleventh century onward generally took form of expulsions, with some exceptions, such as conversions of Jews in southern Italy of the 13th century, which were carried out by Dominican Inquisitors but instigated by King Charles II of Naples.<sup id=\"cite_ref-:0_1-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-:0-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>Jews were forced to convert to Christianity by the Crusaders in Lorraine, on the Lower Rhine, in Bavaria and Bohemia, in Mainz and in Worms.<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h3><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Early_modern_Iberian_peninsula\">Early modern Iberian peninsula</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=History_of_Jewish_conversion_to_Christianity&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: Early modern Iberian peninsula\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h3>\n<div role=\"note\" class=\"hatnote navigation-not-searchable\">Main article: <a href=\"/wiki/Converso\" title=\"Converso\">Converso</a></div>\n<div role=\"note\" class=\"hatnote navigation-not-searchable\">See also: <a href=\"/wiki/Marrano\" title=\"Marrano\">Marrano</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Spanish_Inquisition\" title=\"Spanish Inquisition\">Spanish Inquisition</a></div>\n<p>The majority of Spain's Jews converted to Christianity as a result of <a href=\"/wiki/Pogroms\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Pogroms\">pogroms</a> in 1391.<sup class=\"noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact\" style=\"white-space:nowrap;\">&#91;<i><a href=\"/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed\" title=\"Wikipedia:Citation needed\"><span title=\"This claim needs references to reliable sources. (September 2017)\">citation needed</span></a></i>&#93;</sup>  Those remaining practicing Jews were expelled by the <a href=\"/wiki/Catholic_monarchs\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Catholic monarchs\">Catholic monarchs</a> <a href=\"/wiki/Ferdinand_I_of_Spain\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Ferdinand I of Spain\">Ferdinand</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Isabella_I_of_Spain\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Isabella I of Spain\">Isabella</a> in the <a href=\"/wiki/Alhambra_Decree\" title=\"Alhambra Decree\">Alhambra Decree</a> in 1492, following the Christian <a href=\"/wiki/Reconquista\" title=\"Reconquista\">Reconquest</a> of Spain. As a result of the Alhambra Decree and persecution in prior years, over 200,000 Jews converted to Catholicism and between 40,000 and 100,000 were expelled.<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>Meanwhile in Portugal, although an order for their expulsion was given in 1496, only a handful were allowed to leave, the rest being forced to convert.<sup id=\"cite_ref-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h3><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Eastern_Europe\">Eastern Europe</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=History_of_Jewish_conversion_to_Christianity&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4\" title=\"Edit section: Eastern Europe\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h3>\n<p>Between the years of 1648 and 1649, a large-scale uprising of Cossacks and Ukrainian peasants led by <a href=\"/wiki/Bohdan_Khmelnytsky\" title=\"Bohdan Khmelnytsky\">Bohdan Khmelnytsky</a> swept through the <a href=\"/wiki/Polish%E2%80%93Lithuanian_Commonwealth\" title=\"Polish\u2013Lithuanian Commonwealth\">Polish\u2013Lithuanian Commonwealth</a>, the area of today\u2019s Ukraine. In the course of the fighting, there were many Jewish casualties, and many Jewish communities were destroyed. A large number also converted to <a href=\"/wiki/Eastern_Orthodox_Church\" title=\"Eastern Orthodox Church\">Eastern Orthodoxy</a>.\n</p><p>In the 18th century, <a href=\"/wiki/Elizabeth_of_Russia\" title=\"Elizabeth of Russia\">Elizabeth of Russia</a> launched a campaign of forced conversion of Russia's non-Orthodox subjects, including Muslims and Jews.<sup id=\"cite_ref-5\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>Also, in the second half of the 18th century, a mass conversion to Catholicism occurred by followers of <a href=\"/wiki/Jacob_Frank\" title=\"Jacob Frank\">Jacob Frank</a>.\n</p>\n<h3><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Post-Enlightenment\">Post-Enlightenment</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=History_of_Jewish_conversion_to_Christianity&amp;action=edit&amp;section=5\" title=\"Edit section: Post-Enlightenment\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h3>\n<p>Though forced conversions were less common in the 20th century, missionary activity remained strong, and many Jews chose to convert in order to integrate into secular society. A critical period in Britain followed when many of the chief <a href=\"/wiki/Sephardic\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Sephardic\">Sephardic</a> families \u2014 including the Bernals, <a href=\"/wiki/Furtado\" title=\"Furtado\">Furtados</a>, Ricardos, <a href=\"/wiki/Disraeli\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Disraeli\">Disraelis</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Ximenes\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Ximenes\">Ximenes</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Lopez\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Lopez\">Lopezs</a> and Uzziellis joined the church.<sup id=\"cite_ref-:1_6-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-:1-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-7\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-7\">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>Germany had three main periods of conversion, the first beginning during the <a href=\"/wiki/Moses_Mendelssohn\" title=\"Moses Mendelssohn\">Mendelssohnian</a> era and a second wave occurred during the first half of the 19th century. A list of 32 Jewish families and 18 unmarried Jews who had recently converted was given by <a href=\"/wiki/David_Friedlander\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"David Friedlander\">David Friedlander</a> to <a href=\"/wiki/Prussian\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Prussian\">Prussian</a> State Chancellor <a href=\"/wiki/Hardenberg\" title=\"Hardenberg\">Hardenberg</a> in 1811.<sup id=\"cite_ref-8\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-8\">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup> In the eight old Prussian provinces between the years of 1816-43, during the reign of <a href=\"/wiki/Frederick_William_III.\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Frederick William III.\">Frederick William III.</a>, 3,984 Jews were baptized, among them the many of richest and most cultured<sup id=\"cite_ref-9\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-9\">&#91;9&#93;</a></sup> (2,200 from 1822\u20131840, according to the Jewish Encyclopedia). The third and longest period of secession was due to <a href=\"/wiki/Anti-Semitic\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Anti-Semitic\">antisemitism</a>, and began in the year 1880. Across the German states, with the exception of <a href=\"/wiki/Austria\" title=\"Austria\">Austria</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/France\" title=\"France\">France</a>, many Jews obtained high stations and large revenues in return for their renouncing Judaism.<sup id=\"cite_ref-:1_6-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-:1-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>40,000 Russians alone are believed to have been converted between 1836 and 1875.<sup id=\"cite_ref-10\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-10\">&#91;10&#93;</a></sup> while in Britain during that period, the number has been estimated at 50,000.<sup id=\"cite_ref-11\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-11\">&#91;11&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>Various estimates have been put forward as to the total number of conversions during the 19th century. One Christian encyclopedia writes that the number exceeded 100,000;<sup id=\"cite_ref-12\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-12\">&#91;12&#93;</a></sup> while the Jewish Encyclopedia records approximately 190,000.<sup id=\"cite_ref-13\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-13\">&#91;13&#93;</a></sup> Other contemporary sources put the number at 130,000<sup id=\"cite_ref-14\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-14\">&#91;14&#93;</a></sup> or even as many as 250,000.<sup id=\"cite_ref-15\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-15\">&#91;15&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>As a result of the high rate of conversion, many Christians can be found with a measure of Jewish parentage. In 1930s Germany, Nazi officials discovered that the German Christian population with some level of Jewish ancestry almost equalled that of the Jewish community of just over five hundred thousand.<sup id=\"cite_ref-16\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-16\">&#91;16&#93;</a></sup> Today, according to 2013 data from the <a href=\"/wiki/Pew_Research_Center\" title=\"Pew Research Center\">Pew Research Center</a>, about 1.6 million adult <a href=\"/wiki/American_Jews\" title=\"American Jews\">American Jews</a> identify themselves as <a href=\"/wiki/Christians\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Christians\">Christians</a>, most of them <a href=\"/wiki/Protestant\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Protestant\">Protestant</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-17\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-17\">&#91;17&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-:2_18-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-:2-18\">&#91;18&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-19\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-19\">&#91;19&#93;</a></sup> Of those, most were raised as Jews or are Jews by ancestry.<sup id=\"cite_ref-:2_18-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-:2-18\">&#91;18&#93;</a></sup> According to a 2012 study 17% of <a href=\"/wiki/History_of_the_Jews_in_Russia\" title=\"History of the Jews in Russia\">Jews in Russia</a> identify themselves as <a href=\"/wiki/Christians\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Christians\">Christians</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-20\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-20\">&#91;20&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-21\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-21\">&#91;21&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=History_of_Jewish_conversion_to_Christianity&amp;action=edit&amp;section=6\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap mw-references-columns\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-:0-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-:0_1-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-:0_1-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation book\">Fran\u00e7ois., Soyer, (2007). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/311601500\"><i>The persecution of the Jews and Muslims of Portugal&#160;: King Manuel I and the end of religious tolerance (1496-7)</i></a>. Leiden: Brill. <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/9789047431558\" title=\"Special:BookSources/9789047431558\">9789047431558</a>. <a href=\"/wiki/OCLC\" title=\"OCLC\">OCLC</a>&#160;<a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"//www.worldcat.org/oclc/311601500\">311601500</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=The+persecution+of+the+Jews+and+Muslims+of+Portugal+%3A+King+Manuel+I+and+the+end+of+religious+tolerance+%281496-7%29&amp;rft.place=Leiden&amp;rft.pub=Brill&amp;rft.date=2007&amp;rft_id=info%3Aoclcnum%2F311601500&amp;rft.isbn=9789047431558&amp;rft.aulast=Fran%C3%A7ois.&amp;rft.aufirst=Soyer%2C&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.worldcat.org%2Foclc%2F311601500&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AHistory+of+Jewish+conversion+to+Christianity\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation book\">Abraham Joshua Heschel, Joachim Neugroschel, Sylvia Heschel (1983). <i>Maimonides: A Biography</i>. Macmillan. p.&#160;43.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Maimonides%3A+A+Biography&amp;rft.pages=43&amp;rft.pub=Macmillan&amp;rft.date=1983&amp;rft.au=Abraham+Joshua+Heschel%2C+Joachim+Neugroschel%2C+Sylvia+Heschel&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AHistory+of+Jewish+conversion+to+Christianity\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span><span class=\"citation-comment\" style=\"display:none; color:#33aa33; margin-left:0.3em\">CS1 maint: Multiple names: authors list (<a href=\"/wiki/Category:CS1_maint:_Multiple_names:_authors_list\" title=\"Category:CS1 maint: Multiple names: authors list\">link</a>) </span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-3\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation book\">P\u00e9rez, Joseph (2012). <i>History of a Tragedy. p. 17</i>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=History+of+a+Tragedy.+p.+17.&amp;rft.date=2012&amp;rft.aulast=P%C3%A9rez&amp;rft.aufirst=Joseph&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AHistory+of+Jewish+conversion+to+Christianity\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-4\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-4\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation book\">Fran\u00e7ois., Soyer, (2007). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/311601500\"><i>The persecution of the Jews and Muslims of Portugal&#160;: King Manuel I and the end of religious tolerance (1496-7)</i></a>. Leiden: Brill. <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/9789047431558\" title=\"Special:BookSources/9789047431558\">9789047431558</a>. <a href=\"/wiki/OCLC\" title=\"OCLC\">OCLC</a>&#160;<a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"//www.worldcat.org/oclc/311601500\">311601500</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=The+persecution+of+the+Jews+and+Muslims+of+Portugal+%3A+King+Manuel+I+and+the+end+of+religious+tolerance+%281496-7%29&amp;rft.place=Leiden&amp;rft.pub=Brill&amp;rft.date=2007&amp;rft_id=info%3Aoclcnum%2F311601500&amp;rft.isbn=9789047431558&amp;rft.aulast=Fran%C3%A7ois.&amp;rft.aufirst=Soyer%2C&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.worldcat.org%2Foclc%2F311601500&amp;rfr_id=info%3